Events are one of the most natural ways for people to discover each other ‚Äî not by chatting, but by showing up to something they care about. Our events are designed to be lightweight, informal, and useful. They create opportunities for live connection without pressure or performance.

We use the Events feature in Discord to schedule sessions ranging from working circles and community jams to informal co-working, conversations, and live workshops. Most of these take place in the üõãÔ∏è-hangout multi-media channel, although other tools like Zoom and Google Meet may get used. Some events are hosted by the core team. Others are led by Circle members or invited guests. The goal is always the same: meaningful moments that create connection. Joining an event doesn‚Äôt mean you have to speak, present, or stay the whole time. Come as you are, stay as long as it‚Äôs useful, and feel free to quietly observe if that‚Äôs what you need.

Anyone can propose and host an event. If there‚Äôs something you‚Äôd like to bring to the community ‚Äî a topic to explore, a working session, or just a space to think out loud ‚Äî you‚Äôre welcome to offer it. You can also share externally hosted events that may be valuable to others. If you‚Äôve come across something worth attending ‚Äî a talk, a retreat, a launch, a roundtable ‚Äî create an event so others can find it easily.

Keep an eye on the Events area in Discord for upcoming sessions Watch the üì£-updates channel for announcements, highlights and recaps Follow any Circles that interest you ‚Äî they may run their own events too You don‚Äôt have to attend live to benefit. Many events are followed by short recaps or become reference points for future conversations. This is not about attending everything. It‚Äôs about surfacing the right moments at the right time, so the network continues to feel alive, even when you participate fractionally. Tune in to build deeper connections with other members, leading to new possibilities.

Kudos is our simple way to recognise the people who make this space better ‚Äî not through volume, but through presence, generosity, clarity, and care. This isn‚Äôt about likes, popularity, or rewarding performance. Kudos is about appreciation. It‚Äôs about giving someone a moment of visibility for how they showed up.

In most networks, recognition tends to go to the loudest voice or the most visible profile. We‚Äôre trying something different here. We believe people should be recognised when others notice something real in how they act, speak, or support. That could be for helping you directly, or just for showing a trait you value. Maybe someone brought calm to a difficult thread, offered insight in a moment of tension, or made progress quietly and without fanfare. These small acts are often overlooked in busy networks. Here, they‚Äôre surfaced with intention.

Kudos is currently run through a single thread (üéÅ-give-kudos), with a new one created each week. Here‚Äôs what to do: Post one message per Kudos Tag the person you‚Äôre recognising Say clearly what you‚Äôre appreciating ‚Äî keep it short, but specific Use emoji reactions to support others‚Äô posts No replies or discussions ‚Äî the space is for recognition only If a message isn‚Äôt a Kudos, it will be removed to keep the signal clean.

This is a manual system for now. Behind the scenes, we‚Äôre building a more structured recognition engine that will: Capture peer-to-peer recognition over time Help people discover others through traits and contributions Form the foundation for a future Trust Score system You can help shape that system by joining the Trust Protocol Circle. But for now, this is where it starts. Quiet moments of appreciation that make people feel seen. When done well, it shifts the culture ‚Äî from status-seeking to mutual uplift. So if someone helped you this week, or reminded you of the kind of person you want to be, say so. Publicly. Simply. Generously.

The üéØ-my-focus-this-week channel exists to help members be seen for what they care about ‚Äî not just what they‚Äôve already done. Each member has a dedicated space where they can share what they‚Äôre focusing on this week. It‚Äôs a simple broadcast that can lead to support, visibility, and unexpected alignment with others.

We often underestimate how helpful it is to let others know where our attention is. By sharing what you‚Äôre working on, you‚Äôre not asking for validation ‚Äî you‚Äôre opening a door to collaboration, insight, or encouragement. Sometimes someone will offer to help. Sometimes someone will simply notice. Both are valuable. It is a great way to discover and connect with well-aligned members too. Over time, these short weekly declarations build a subtle narrative of progress. They help others understand who you are and what you value, without requiring performance or updates.

Every member gets a dedicated space within üéØ-my-focus-this-week Share a short summary of your focus for the week (1‚Äì2 lines is fine) Optionally include how others can support you Any related conversations happen in the same space
‚ÄúThis week I‚Äôm refining my landing page and testing it with 5 users. Would love input if you‚Äôve done early-stage UX.‚Äù

You can follow posts from members whose journeys resonate with yours. This makes it easy to stay connected without being overwhelmed by updates from everyone. Active posts surface to the top, so timely efforts are more visible. It‚Äôs an easy way to discover people who are doing meaningful work ‚Äî right now. You don‚Äôt have to post every week. You don‚Äôt have to read every post. But if you use this space with intention, it quietly builds context and connection over time.

The üõãÔ∏è-hangout is our virtual water cooler ‚Äî a space for relaxed, spontaneous conversations without an agenda. Whether you're looking to meet someone new, bounce ideas, or just take a breather and see who‚Äôs around, Hangout is open.

Unlike scheduled calls or formal events, Hangout is designed for serendipity. It‚Äôs where you might drop in and find a familiar face or meet someone you‚Äôve never spoken to before. It‚Äôs especially useful for people who prefer informal networking. You don‚Äôt need a topic or a reason ‚Äî just curiosity.

Drop into the voice/video room whenever you're free If you're the first one there, feel free to stay for a bit ‚Äî someone may spot you and join If no one turns up, no problem ‚Äî it‚Äôs a low-commitment way to be open to conversation If you prefer structure, you can create an event to let others know when you‚Äôll be around Conversations can be 1-1 or group ‚Äî others are welcome to huddle in and join ongoing discussions

Traditional speed networking can feel forced. This isn‚Äôt that. Hangout is built around ease and presence. It‚Äôs a way to connect without pressure, while doing other things or just taking a moment away from your usual flow. Some of the best ideas and connections emerge from unplanned interactions. This is a space that makes those possible. So if you‚Äôve got a few minutes and an open mind, swing by. You never know who you might meet.

The ü§Ø-i-am-stuck space exists for when you hit a wall ‚Äî technical, creative, strategic, or otherwise. It‚Äôs a simple mechanism to surface stuck points so others can help, without needing long context or formal asks.

We all get stuck. Sometimes it‚Äôs a problem we don‚Äôt know how to solve. Other times it‚Äôs something that just needs talking out loud. This channel is a place to say so. Sharing that you‚Äôre stuck is not a weakness. It‚Äôs a strength. It signals honesty, momentum, and a willingness to move through challenge. More often than not, someone else has been there ‚Äî and is happy to help. By sharing your problem, you create an opportunity for others to give back.

Start a new post with a short description of what you‚Äôre stuck on Keep it clear and specific ‚Äî enough that others can respond usefully Tag your post with one of the available categories (e.g. Brainstorm, Advice, Review, Pointers, Introductions, etc.) Use the thread to clarify or explore ‚Äî but avoid turning it into a side discussion
‚ÄúI‚Äôm struggling to articulate the core benefit of my product to first-time visitors. If anyone‚Äôs good at landing page messaging, I‚Äôd love a second look.‚Äù

This isn‚Äôt just about solving blockers. It‚Äôs about creating a culture where support is normal and asking for help is easy. Even if your stuck moment doesn‚Äôt get solved immediately, naming it creates visibility and sometimes leads to conversations that spark something later. Often the act of articulating your blocker is sufficient to unblock. Try it. You don‚Äôt have to post often ‚Äî but if you find yourself spinning your wheels, this might be the fastest way out.

The üçï-share channel is a place to surface useful information that others in the network might benefit from ‚Äî and to spark the kinds of deeper conversations and connections that start with curiosity. Whether it‚Äôs a tool, an opportunity, or an idea that resonated with you, sharing it here builds a collective knowledge base and helps the network stay relevant and resourceful.

The content shared here can be practical, inspirational, or thought-provoking. It doesn‚Äôt have to be something you created ‚Äî just something you came across and thought might be useful for others. Use the appropriate tag when posting so others can easily find what‚Äôs most relevant to them. Some of the categories include: Event ‚Äì an upcoming gathering, workshop, or talk others might benefit from (although using Events is better) Tool ‚Äì anything that makes work, collaboration, or creativity easier Book ‚Äì something worth reading or referring back to Report ‚Äì new research, frameworks, or insights Podcast / Video ‚Äì content that educates, inspires, or provokes fresh thinking Community ‚Äì other networks, forums, or platforms aligned with our values Job Opportunity / Fellowship / Funding ‚Äì openings or resources that could support someone‚Äôs journey Miscellaneous ‚Äì anything useful that doesn‚Äôt yet fit the above (we review this regularly to improve tagging)

Start a new post with a brief intro to what you‚Äôre sharing and why it‚Äôs relevant Add the appropriate tag Keep the description short, but consider adding context or a personal insight Others can react with emojis or add comments if they want to explore the topic further This isn‚Äôt meant to be a high-chatter space. Some posts will start conversations, others will quietly inform. Both are valuable.

Over time, this channel becomes a curated feed of what the network values ‚Äî and a reflection of the topics that matter most. It's a way to stay informed without scrolling endlessly, and a way to contribute without pressure. Whether you're looking for new thinking or looking to offer it, this is a good place to start.

‚òïÔ∏è-tea-break is the most relaxed space in the network ‚Äî a corner to share lighthearted finds, entertaining moments, and anything that might brighten someone‚Äôs day. It‚Äôs where we let our curiosity and personalities show, and sometimes where the best conversations begin.

Even in focused, intentional communities, there‚Äôs room for play. Tea Break offers a window into what moves, delights, or amuses us ‚Äî and those glimpses can spark surprising connections. You might find a clever article, a funny video, a beautiful piece of art, or just something random that made you think. You might share something about where you‚Äôre from, what you‚Äôre doing, or how you unwind. There‚Äôs no expectation to be profound here. Just bring your humanity.

Share something light, fun, or personally meaningful Keep it respectful and inclusive ‚Äî moderation is slightly tighter here to maintain tone Use threads to explore a shared interest or idea, but keep the overall vibe easygoing You‚Äôre welcome to mute or hide this channel if you prefer to engage only with more focused spaces

While Tea Break is not about serious strategy or deep dives, it‚Äôs still part of the bigger picture. A space like this helps the community breathe. It lets people show up in low-stakes ways, which can lead to stronger trust elsewhere. Sometimes, a shared laugh or a common interest is what turns a stranger into a collaborator. So if you‚Äôve got something worth a smile, share it. You never know where it might lead.

The Updates channel (üì£-updates) is where we keep you in the loop ‚Äî clearly, calmly, and without noise. We use it to share key changes, new features, moments worth noting, and behind-the-scenes shifts. It‚Äôs designed to help you stay informed without having to dig through channels or be constantly active.

Most online spaces reward staying tuned in all the time. That‚Äôs not our model. Here, we actively support fractional participation, giving you the ability to dip in when it suits you, without missing what matters. The Updates channel is one of the ways we make that possible. Whether you‚Äôve been away for a few days or a few weeks, you can scroll back and quickly catch up. No trawling. No overwhelm.
documents.s: A Calm Pulse, Not a Constant Feed

documents.t: We encourage members to check this channel regularly, not out of urgency, but more as a rhythm. It helps you stay in sync with the evolution of the network and see what‚Äôs unfolding behind the scenes. You won‚Äôt find hype here. Just thoughtful, well-paced updates that keep you connected without demanding your attention. This space is built for people who value focus. The Updates channel helps you keep it.

Circles are the foundation of how meaningful relationships, collaboration, and discovery take shape in this space. Rather than relying on constant chatter or passive feeds, we use Circles to create purposeful spaces where members can connect with relevance, act together, and grow their networks with intention.

We support two distinct types of Circles: Action Circles: Small, focused groups of up to 10 members. These exist to collaborate on short-term projects, think tanks, or longer-term ventures. They are designed to help you move ideas forward without noise or friction. Networking Circles: Larger groups, up to 150 members, built around shared interests or goals. These provide a space for shameless networking ‚Äî connecting with others who are intentionally aligned and open to exploring synergies. We believe in shameless networking. When done with integrity, it‚Äôs one of the most valuable tools for progress. Circles make it easier to do this with structure and consent.

Each Circle shares regular updates in the üåê-join-circles channel. This allows members who aren‚Äôt part of the group to stay informed and supportive without having to participate actively. It‚Äôs a simple way to follow the story of a Circle and step in when you‚Äôre ready or available.
documents.s: Staying in the Loop, Even When You're Not Inside

documents.t: Every Circle has a Lead who holds responsibility for keeping the group coherent and moving. For action-focused Circles, the Lead may take on a stronger role ‚Äî especially in Venture Circles, where they are empowered to make decisions on behalf of the group to avoid stagnation. Leads can also choose to build a small support group around them to help with facilitation and reduce pressure. The tone and pace of the Circle is shaped by the Lead‚Äôs intent, and the clarity of that leadership helps the group avoid endless discussion and stay focused on action.

If you see a Circle that interests you, reach out to the Circle Lead directly (you‚Äôll find their name in the overview). These conversations usually happen 1-on-1 via DMs or short calls. Especially in action circles, Leads will often evaluate your interest carefully to make sure there‚Äôs alignment ‚Äî both for your sake and the group‚Äôs. To avoid distraction, you‚Äôll only see Circles you‚Äôre a part of in your sidebar. This helps keep the experience clean and focused.

Starting a Circle is easy. Start a message to PaveTheChange.org on Discord with your idea. If it‚Äôs a good fit, we‚Äôll set it up for you ‚Äî as long as you‚Äôre happy to step into the role of Circle Lead. That‚Äôs our one requirement. A Circle needs someone who will hold the space and guide its rhythm. This is a system designed to give you leverage, not load. Use it when the moment calls for it, and leave it behind when it doesn‚Äôt.

The üõ°Ô∏è-trust-protocol is where we co-create the future of recognition and connection in this network. It‚Äôs a space for members who want to go deeper ‚Äî shaping the systems behind how we notice, appreciate, and elevate one another, and laying the groundwork for a more meaningful kind of online reputation.

Most digital spaces reward attention, not contribution. We‚Äôre building something different ‚Äî a system that helps surface who‚Äôs showing up with generosity, thoughtfulness, and action. But designing that system well requires the same qualities. That‚Äôs why this Circle exists: to bring together people who want to help us: Design and test the recognition system (Kudos, Trust Score, etc.) Ensure the system is human-first, low-noise, and built for long-term trust Explore cultural and technical implications of what we‚Äôre building Pilot early versions, reflect on the experience, and refine as we go

You don‚Äôt need to be a designer or engineer to contribute ‚Äî just thoughtful, curious, and committed to creating something better. As a member of this Circle, you might: Join periodic working sessions Contribute ideas, critiques, or stories from other networks Help test new features and provide feedback Support others in applying the system meaningfully

Send a message to the Circle Lead and express your interest. It will usually follow a quick chat to align on intent and fit. This helps keep the group focused and productive. Whether you're here to shape the tech, refine the culture, or just be part of something early and important ‚Äî we welcome you. Let‚Äôs build something that truly earns trust.
Last updated: May 10, 2025 Welcome to PaveTheChange.org. Your privacy matters to us. This Privacy Policy outlines how we collect, use, and protect your information when you engage with our platform.

We may collect the following types of information: Personal details you choose to provide (e.g. first name, last name, country, timezone, MBTI type, LinkedIn URL, etc.) Data from platform interactions (e.g. submitted forms, preferences, and collaboration activity) Metadata such as timestamps and engagement history Anonymous usage analytics (if enabled)

We use your information to: Facilitate collaboration between members Match you with others who can support your dreams and goals Improve the functionality, usability, and overall experience of our platform We do not sell your data. Your information is used solely to enhance your participation and community interaction.
All data is stored securely on Supabase, which follows industry-standard practices for encryption, access control, and data protection.

We operate an off-chain token system within our platform database. Tokens may be used for recognition and collaboration tracking. Only upon reaching specific thresholds (as defined by the platform) may users request on-chain transfers to their digital wallet.
You have the right to: Access your personal information Request updates or deletions Withdraw participation at any time To exercise your rights, contact us at hello@pavethechange.org.

We use cookies and other browser storage mechanisms (such as local and session storage) to support essential functionality and improve your experience on the platform. This includes, but is not limited to, remembering preferences, maintaining login sessions, and securely storing data on your device. We do not use cookies or browser storage for third-party tracking or advertising purposes. If our usage practices change significantly, we will update this policy accordingly.
This policy may be updated periodically. The latest version will always be available here with the updated date shown above.
Questions? Email us at hello@pavethechange.org.

This space is designed to help you discover others who care about the things you care about, and to be quietly recognised for how you show up ‚Äî not how often or how loudly. We call this the Trust Network. It‚Äôs a lightweight system designed for high-signal, low-noise connection. Every channel, feature, and interaction has been carefully shaped to reduce noise, avoid performance, and create space for real human momentum. The broader goal is to connect a million dreams by 2030. That‚Äôs what Million Dreams is about ‚Äî creating the conditions for aligned people to find each other, build trust, and move forward without the pressure of algorithms, followers, or feeds.

This guide introduces each of the channels inside our Discord space. These aren‚Äôt traditional discussion channels. Instead they are tools for connecting and supporting, each designed to serve a distinct purpose. We‚Äôve created this to: Help you understand the why behind each space Make it easy to participate lightly but meaningfully Invite you to use the system in a way that supports your own journey This site is not to teach you how to use Discord. Our focus is on helping you understand how we‚Äôre using it, so that you can make the most our of our work.

You don‚Äôt need to use everything. You don‚Äôt need to be everywhere. The system is designed to work even with light participation. If you ever feel stuck, let others know and ask for help. If someone helped you this week, give them a Kudos generously. Let others know your focus for this week and spark a conversation with other like-minded members and connect on topics that are on top of your mind. You don‚Äôt have to do more than that to start showing up here. Thanks for being here. This only works if people like you use it your way ‚Äî with honesty, intent, and just enough visibility to be found when it matters.

documents.t: The üìó-44-stories Circle is a collaborative publishing initiative focused on sharing real, lived experiences with mental health ‚Äî stories from people who have faced struggles and found a way through. By giving voice to these stories, we aim to help those currently suffering and contribute to normalising a topic that still carries too much silence and stigma.

This is an action Circle with a clear and powerful outcome: a published book of 44 stories. Each story will be co-created, carefully held, and shared with purpose. Participants in the Circle actively contribute to the development of this project. That could mean sharing your own story, helping shape someone else‚Äôs, supporting editorial work, or contributing to the publishing and outreach process. You don‚Äôt need to give all your time ‚Äî just a steady, fractional commitment and the willingness to support a shared goal.

If you're curious about the Circle but not ready to participate directly, you're welcome to follow updates on this Circle. Just hit the follow button and you‚Äôll be notified when updates are shared. If you‚Äôd like to join and contribute, reach out to the Circle Lead, who with discuss this in more detail.

Mental health challenges are part of many people‚Äôs journeys ‚Äî but the silence around them creates unnecessary isolation. By telling these stories together, we‚Äôre making space for understanding, hope, and solidarity. This is storytelling with a purpose. And if you're here, you might have something important to bring to it.

We provide the platform "as is" without warranties of any kind. Participation is voluntary and outcomes are not guaranteed. We are not responsible for any decisions or collaborations that occur through the platform.
These terms may change. The most recent version will always be posted here. Your continued use of the platform signifies your acceptance of any updates.
